cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "Architecture Determines Observability in Transformers"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Carmichael
    given-names: Thomas
version: "3.4.0"
date-released: "2026-04-28"
license: MIT
doi: "10.5281/zenodo.19435674"
repository-code: "https://github.com/tmcarmichael/nn-observability"
abstract: "Autoregressive transformers make high-confidence errors, but activation monitoring can catch them only if the model preserves an internal signal that output confidence does not expose. We show that this preservation is determined by architecture and training recipe. Observability is defined as the linear readability of per-token decision quality from frozen mid-layer activations after controlling for output confidence; this correction is essential, because confidence controls absorb on average 57.7% of raw probe-loss correlation across 25 models (16 cross-family, 9 Pythia) across 7 families. Some models preserve a residual signal, and part of it is output-independent: trained predictors on the final-layer representation do not recover it. But the signal is not guaranteed. In Pythia's controlled suite, every tested run sharing the (24 layers, 16 heads) configuration collapses to pcorr approximately 0.10 across a 3.5x parameter gap and two Pile variants, while six other configurations occupy a separated healthy band (0.21 to 0.38). The output-controlled residual collapses at the same points: the architecture effect is not a failure of linear readout but the disappearance of the output-independent component that activation monitors need. Checkpoint dynamics show this collapse is training-emergent: both matched-width configurations are healthy at the earliest measured checkpoint, but training erases the output-independent component in the (24L, 16H) class. The collapse reproduces observationally across families at recipe-dependent configurations: Qwen and Llama differ by 2.9x at matched 3B scale with non-overlapping probe-seed distributions, while Mistral 7B and Llama 3.1 8B share broad architectural shape yet diverge. Nonlinear probes and alternative layer choices do not recover healthy-range signal where collapse occurs. A WikiText-trained observer catches a non-overlapping downstream QA error class without task-specific training; at 20% flag rate, seven of nine model-task cells fall between 10.9% and 13.4%. Architecture selection is a monitoring decision."
keywords:
  - neural network observability
  - transformer interpretability
  - decision quality
  - learned probes
  - confidence controls
  - architecture-dependent readability
  - partial correlation
  - cross-family evaluation
  - downstream QA transfer
